# Psychology-First UX — Behavioral Economics & Neuromarketing

## HICK'S LAW — Navigation
- Maximum 5 navigation links — no more, no exceptions
- Current Charm Payments nav (correct order):
  Solutions · Charm Cards · How It Works · Pricing · Contact
- No dropdowns — flat nav only
- Mobile menu mirrors desktop exactly
- Fewer choices = faster decisions = higher conversion

## VON RESTORFF ISOLATION EFFECT — CTA Color
- Primary CTA uses brand-accent (#9edd05) ONLY
- #9edd05 must NOT appear as a background color anywhere
  except on primary CTA buttons and key highlights
- This makes the CTA visually isolated — the eye finds it
  instantly without conscious effort
- Secondary actions use btn-outline (transparent/border)
- Never use btn-accent for decorative elements — it dilutes
  the isolation effect

## F-PATTERN & Z-PATTERN LAYOUTS
- Hero: headline top-left, subheadline below, CTA bottom-left,
  image right — follows F-pattern eye movement
- Feature sections: alternate image left/right to create Z-pattern
  across the page scroll
- Place the highest-value copy (headline, value prop, price)
  in the top-left of every section — that is where eyes land first
- Never center-align body copy — left-align for readability
  and F-pattern compliance (headlines and labels may center)

## ZEIGARNIK EFFECT — Progress & Completion
- Multi-step forms MUST show a visual progress bar
- Apply form: show "Step X of 4" with filled progress indicator
- Progress bar uses brand-accent (#9edd05) fill on brand-light track
- Incomplete state creates psychological drive to finish
- Never show all form fields at once — step-by-step reduces
  abandonment by reducing perceived effort
- Step labels: "Business Info" · "Owner Info" ·
  "Banking Info" · "Review & Submit"

## MICRO-INTERACTIONS — Instant Variable Reward
- All hover states: transition duration 200ms exactly
- Button hover: scale(1.02) + slight shadow increase
- Card hover: translateY(-4px) + shadow increase
- Link hover: color shift to brand-accent in 200ms
- Form input focus: border color → brand-accent in 200ms
- Success states: checkmark animation 200ms ease-out
- Never use transitions longer than 300ms on interactive elements
- Satisfies user need for immediate feedback = dopamine loop

## SOCIAL PROOF PLACEMENT — Trust Anchoring
- Trust signals must appear BEFORE the price is shown
- Page order: Hero → Social Proof → Features → Pricing
- Never show pricing before establishing credibility
- Social proof types in priority order:
  1. Merchant count or processing volume
  2. Named testimonials with photo, name, business
  3. Partner/processor logos (NMI, First Data, Fiserv, Visa, MC)
  4. Security badges (PCI DSS, SSL)
- Position trust signals within first 2 scrolls (above ~1400px)

## COGNITIVE LOAD REDUCTION — 60-30-10 Color Rule
- 60% — neutral/white/brand-light backgrounds
- 30% — brand-dark (#0c3a30) for text and dark sections
- 10% — brand-accent (#9edd05) for CTAs and highlights ONLY
- Generous white space: section-ptb (100px top/bottom)
- Cards: minimum 40px padding (p-10)
- Never stack more than 3 competing visual elements in one
  viewport — one hero image, one headline, one CTA per fold
- Visual noise kills conversion — when in doubt, remove

## PRINCIPLE OF LEAST EFFORT — Button & CTA Placement
- Primary CTA must be reachable without moving the mouse far
  from natural resting position (center-right of viewport)
- Hero CTA: left column, vertically centered in viewport
- Sticky nav CTA: top-right (always visible, always reachable)
- Final section CTA: center of page, large, high contrast
- Never make the user search for how to take action

## AESTHETIC-USABILITY EFFECT
- Beautiful design makes users more forgiving of bugs
- Users perceive premium-looking sites as more trustworthy
- Consistent spacing, typography, and color = perceived quality
- Charm Payments must feel as polished as Stripe or Brex
- If a section looks "good enough" — it is not good enough

## LOSS AVERSION — Copy Framing
- Frame benefits as avoiding loss, not gaining benefit
- Bad: "Get faster payments"
- Good: "Stop waiting 3-5 days for your money"
- Bad: "Low processing fees"
- Good: "Keep more of every sale"
- Bad: "Apply today"
- Good: "Don't lose another sale to payment issues"
- Loss framing increases urgency without false scarcity claims

## BEFORE BUILDING ANY PAGE OR COMPONENT
Answer these questions:
1. What is the ONE action the user should take?
2. Where do eyes land first on this page? (F/Z pattern)
3. Is the CTA color isolated from all other brand-accent uses?
4. Does social proof appear before pricing?
5. Is cognitive load minimized — 60-30-10 color, white space?
6. Do all micro-interactions run at exactly 200ms?
7. Is loss aversion framing applied to the primary headline?
